{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JYtNwxoYa6C3QhnEZNwoHq","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Decision Log\n     2→\n     3→Track key architectural and product decisions as they're made.\n     4→\n     5→---\n     6→\n     7→## 2026-02-09 - Initial Setup\n     8→\n     9→### Decision: Coinflip First, Lord of the RNGs Second\n    10→**Date**: 2026-02-09\n    11→**Decision**: Phase 1 will be Coinflip, Phase 2 will be Lord of the RNGs\n    12→**Rationale**: Coinflip and Lord of the RNGs share a VRF-driven fairness path and non-real-time settlement model, letting us validate core settlement/fairness flows before tackling Crash timing complexity.\n    13→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    14→\n    15→### Decision: Standard Anchor Programs (Not BOLT ECS)\n    16→**Date**: 2026-02-17 (revised from 2026-02-09)\n    17→**Decision**: Use standard Anchor `#[program]` / `#[derive(Accounts)]` architecture. Legacy BOLT ECS code removed.\n    18→**Rationale**: BOLT ECS adds unnecessary abstraction for our use case (simple 1v1 games). Standard Anchor is well-documented, widely supported by tooling (bankrun, IDL gen), and simpler to debug. Separate programs per game (coinflip, platform) + shared lib crate for constants.\n    19→**Alternatives considered**: BOLT ECS (original choice, too complex for V1), single monolith program (poor separation of concerns).\n    20→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    21→\n    22→### Decision: Normal Wallets First, Privy Later\n    23→**Date**: 2026-02-09\n    24→**Decision**: Ship normal Solana wallet flow first (Phantom/Solflare), add Privy embedded wallets in V1.5\n    25→**Rationale**: Normal wallets are simpler to validate. Privy adds complexity (session keys, embedded wallet creation) that can be added after core game loop is proven.\n    26→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    27→\n    28→### Decision: Two-Repo Structure\n    29→**Date**: 2026-02-09\n    30→**Decision**: Root repo for project management/docs, `sources/rng-utopia/` as git submodule pointing to code repo\n    31→**Rationale**: Clean separation of project context vs codebase. Allows independent versioning.\n    32→**Status**: ✅ Implemented\n    33→\n    34→### Decision: FE Entrypoint Is apps/platform\n    35→**Date**: 2026-02-11\n    36→**Decision**: Treat `sources/rng-utopia/apps/platform/` as the authoritative frontend runtime entrypoint.\n    37→**Rationale**: This is the currently deployed shell containing active feature mocks; other app folders are scaffolds and not required for FE runtime verification.\n    38→**Alternatives considered**: Building all app scaffolds as hard requirement (`build:all`).\n    39→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    40→\n    41→### Decision: Non-Platform Apps Are Platform-Only Scaffolds\n    42→**Date**: 2026-02-11\n    43→**Decision**: Keep non-platform app folders under `sources/rng-utopia/apps/` as platform-only scaffolds, not standalone deployment targets.\n    44→**Rationale**: Runtime game flows are embedded in `apps/platform` and this preserves structure without forcing standalone Vite app parity for each scaffold.\n    45→**Alternatives considered**: Making each app independently buildable and deployable in the current phase.\n    46→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    47→\n    48→---\n    49→\n    50→## 2026-02-25 - Architecture Pivot\n    51→\n    52→### Decision: Solana Settlement & Fairness Standard (Pivot Doc)\n    53→**Date**: 2026-02-25\n    54→**Decision**: Program-per-game + shared Rust crate (`solana/shared/`), two fairness approaches (VRF + Commit-Reveal), standardized lifecycle with timeout/pause/fee/refund invariants across all 8 games.\n    55→**Rationale**: Consistency across all games, single audit path, compile-time guarantees via shared crate. No shared on-chain kernel — consistency from compilation, not CPI. See `docs/pivot-doc.md` for full architecture.\n    56→**Alternatives considered**: Shared on-chain EscrowKernel program (CPI overhead, larger blast radius), per-game bespoke state machines (inconsistent, harder to audit).\n    57→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    58→\n    59→### Decision: VRF Provider = Orao (MagicBlock dropped)\n    60→**Date**: 2026-02-25\n    61→**Decision**: Replace MagicBlock Ephemeral VRF with **Orao** as the single VRF provider for V1.\n    62→**Rationale**: Orao proved straightforward devnet integration and fast fulfillment in live smoke tests. This gives us one VRF integration path for Coinflip and Lord of RNGs while preserving the pivot architecture.\n    63→**Alternatives considered**: Switchboard (reachable on devnet but required additional callback-consumer wiring for equivalent end-to-end benchmarking), keeping MagicBlock VRF (limited VRF focus, uncertain long-term support).\n    64→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    65→\n    66→### Decision: Crash Fairness Model — VRF + Commit-Reveal (Not HMAC-Only)\n    67→**Date**: 2026-02-25\n    68→**Decision**: Crash uses VRF seed (requested pre-round) + commit-reveal for server result verification. Replaces the HMAC seed chain model.\n    69→**Rationale**: VRF provides unpredictable seed generation without pre-commitment chains. Commit-reveal proves server honesty for the off-chain engine. Same two fairness primitives used across all games — no per-game mechanisms.\n    70→**Alternatives considered**: HMAC seed chain (Bustabit model — works but requires separate pre-commitment infrastructure not shared with other games).\n    71→**Status**: ✅ Locked\n    72→\n    73→---\n    74→\n    75→## Template for New Decisions\n    76→\n    77→```markdown\n    78→### Decision: [Title]\n    79→**Date**: YYYY-MM-DD\n    80→**Decision**: [What was decided]\n    81→**Rationale**: [Why this choice]\n    82→**Alternatives considered**: [Other options]\n    83→**Status**: [✅ Locked / 🟡 Revisitable / ❌ Reversed]\n    84→```\n    85→\n    86→---\n    87→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"71f3d66f-916b-4438-95fb-e3b573af6aa8","uuid":"7bdbbad2-870d-4052-83c6-f509e68cb956","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/rng-utopia/docs/DECISIONS.md","content":"# Decision Log\n\nTrack key architectural and product decisions as they're made.\n\n---\n\n## 2026-02-09 - Initial Setup\n\n### Decision: Coinflip First, Lord of the RNGs Second\n**Date**: 2026-02-09\n**Decision**: Phase 1 will be Coinflip, Phase 2 will be Lord of the RNGs\n**Rationale**: Coinflip and Lord of the RNGs share a VRF-driven fairness path and non-real-time settlement model, letting us validate core settlement/fairness flows before tackling Crash timing complexity.\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n### Decision: Standard Anchor Programs (Not BOLT ECS)\n**Date**: 2026-02-17 (revised from 2026-02-09)\n**Decision**: Use standard Anchor `#[program]` / `#[derive(Accounts)]` architecture. Legacy BOLT ECS code removed.\n**Rationale**: BOLT ECS adds unnecessary abstraction for our use case (simple 1v1 games). Standard Anchor is well-documented, widely supported by tooling (bankrun, IDL gen), and simpler to debug. Separate programs per game (coinflip, platform) + shared lib crate for constants.\n**Alternatives considered**: BOLT ECS (original choice, too complex for V1), single monolith program (poor separation of concerns).\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n### Decision: Normal Wallets First, Privy Later\n**Date**: 2026-02-09\n**Decision**: Ship normal Solana wallet flow first (Phantom/Solflare), add Privy embedded wallets in V1.5\n**Rationale**: Normal wallets are simpler to validate. Privy adds complexity (session keys, embedded wallet creation) that can be added after core game loop is proven.\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n### Decision: Two-Repo Structure\n**Date**: 2026-02-09\n**Decision**: Root repo for project management/docs, `sources/rng-utopia/` as git submodule pointing to code repo\n**Rationale**: Clean separation of project context vs codebase. Allows independent versioning.\n**Status**: ✅ Implemented\n\n### Decision: FE Entrypoint Is apps/platform\n**Date**: 2026-02-11\n**Decision**: Treat `sources/rng-utopia/apps/platform/` as the authoritative frontend runtime entrypoint.\n**Rationale**: This is the currently deployed shell containing active feature mocks; other app folders are scaffolds and not required for FE runtime verification.\n**Alternatives considered**: Building all app scaffolds as hard requirement (`build:all`).\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n### Decision: Non-Platform Apps Are Platform-Only Scaffolds\n**Date**: 2026-02-11\n**Decision**: Keep non-platform app folders under `sources/rng-utopia/apps/` as platform-only scaffolds, not standalone deployment targets.\n**Rationale**: Runtime game flows are embedded in `apps/platform` and this preserves structure without forcing standalone Vite app parity for each scaffold.\n**Alternatives considered**: Making each app independently buildable and deployable in the current phase.\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n---\n\n## 2026-02-25 - Architecture Pivot\n\n### Decision: Solana Settlement & Fairness Standard (Pivot Doc)\n**Date**: 2026-02-25\n**Decision**: Program-per-game + shared Rust crate (`solana/shared/`), two fairness approaches (VRF + Commit-Reveal), standardized lifecycle with timeout/pause/fee/refund invariants across all 8 games.\n**Rationale**: Consistency across all games, single audit path, compile-time guarantees via shared crate. No shared on-chain kernel — consistency from compilation, not CPI. See `docs/pivot-doc.md` for full architecture.\n**Alternatives considered**: Shared on-chain EscrowKernel program (CPI overhead, larger blast radius), per-game bespoke state machines (inconsistent, harder to audit).\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n### Decision: VRF Provider = Orao (MagicBlock dropped)\n**Date**: 2026-02-25\n**Decision**: Replace MagicBlock Ephemeral VRF with **Orao** as the single VRF provider for V1.\n**Rationale**: Orao proved straightforward devnet integration and fast fulfillment in live smoke tests. This gives us one VRF integration path for Coinflip and Lord of RNGs while preserving the pivot architecture.\n**Alternatives considered**: Switchboard (reachable on devnet but required additional callback-consumer wiring for equivalent end-to-end benchmarking), keeping MagicBlock VRF (limited VRF focus, uncertain long-term support).\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n### Decision: Crash Fairness Model — VRF + Commit-Reveal (Not HMAC-Only)\n**Date**: 2026-02-25\n**Decision**: Crash uses VRF seed (requested pre-round) + commit-reveal for server result verification. Replaces the HMAC seed chain model.\n**Rationale**: VRF provides unpredictable seed generation without pre-commitment chains. Commit-reveal proves server honesty for the off-chain engine. Same two fairness primitives used across all games — no per-game mechanisms.\n**Alternatives considered**: HMAC seed chain (Bustabit model — works but requires separate pre-commitment infrastructure not shared with other games).\n**Status**: ✅ Locked\n\n---\n\n## Template for New Decisions\n\n```markdown\n### Decision: [Title]\n**Date**: YYYY-MM-DD\n**Decision**: [What was decided]\n**Rationale**: [Why this choice]\n**Alternatives considered**: [Other options]\n**Status**: [✅ Locked / 🟡 Revisitable / ❌ Reversed]\n```\n\n---\n","numLines":87,"startLine":1,"totalLines":87}}}
