{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FcEmAvcBuVZzzydKpyHFF6","type":"tool_result","content":"    60→### FR-1: Shared Crate — Escrow Helpers (Claim-Based Payout)\n    61→\n    62→Reusable functions for depositing SOL to a round PDA and letting participants claim their funds. Uses a **claim-based payout pattern**: for VRF games, the `claim_payout` instruction reads the VRF result at claim time (no separate settle tx), derives the winner, and transfers funds — all in one tx. For commit-reveal games, the server's reveal instruction writes the outcome, then players claim. Either way, the claim instruction is what moves funds.\n    63→\n    64→**Three-transaction flow for VRF games (e.g., coinflip):**\n    65→1. `create_match` — creator deposits SOL, phase = WAITING\n    66→2. `join_match` — opponent deposits SOL, requests Orao VRF, phase = LOCKED, `resolve_deadline` set\n    67→3. `claim_payout` — either player calls. Reads fulfilled Orao randomness account, derives winner, transfers payout + fee, emits audit event, closes match.\n    68→\n    69→Frontend reads the Orao randomness PDA (free, no tx) to show the result. The claim tx is what settles on-chain.\n    70→\n    71→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    72→- [x] `deposit_to_escrow(from, round_pda, amount)` transfers SOL from player to round PDA via system program CPI <!-- satisfied: escrow.rs:53 transfer_lamports_to_pda; used in create_match.rs:46, join_match.rs:70 -->\n    73→- [x] `claim_payout` reads VRF result at claim time (for VRF games) or reads stored outcome (for commit-reveal games), derives winner, transfers payout <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:104 reads Orao, :107-112 derives winner, :115-126 transfers -->\n    74→- [x] Either participant can trigger claim — payout always goes to the derived winner regardless of caller <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:79-83 allows creator/opponent, :108-112 derives winner; test \"either player can trigger claim\" -->\n    75→- [x] Claim is idempotent — double-claim returns error, does not double-pay <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:76 checks !claimed, PDA closed after claim (:20); test \"rejects double claim\" -->\n    76→- [x] Claim emits an Anchor event with VRF randomness bytes, derived winner, and payout amounts (audit trail — match PDA is closed after claim) <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:156-163 emits MatchSettled; state.rs:55-63 event struct -->\n    77→- [x] `refund(round_pda, caller)` — each depositor calls individually to pull their refund after timeout <!-- satisfied: timeout_cancel.rs:74-77 refunds both via transfer_lamports_from_pda (atomic, design variance) -->\n    78→- [x] `close_round(round_pda, rent_recipient)` closes the PDA and returns rent <!-- satisfied: Anchor close=creator constraint on claim_payout.rs:20, cancel_match.rs:17, timeout_cancel.rs:29 -->\n    79→- [x] No escrow function touches fee math (fees handled separately in FR-3) <!-- satisfied: escrow.rs has only lamport transfer functions; fees in fees.rs, called separately in claim_payout.rs:116 -->\n    80→- [ ] **Claimable games query**: match PDAs in LOCKED phase (VRF fulfilled) or SETTLED phase (commit-reveal settled) with `claimed == false` are discoverable via `getProgramAccounts` filter by player pubkey + phase. Frontend must maintain a \"claimable / unresolved games\" list per user. <!-- gap: frontend chain.ts only has fetchAllOpenMatches (Waiting phase); no claimable-per-user query exists -->\n    81→\n    82→### FR-2: Commit-Reveal Verifier\n    83→\n    84→Self-built module (~50 lines Rust) for server result verification. The server commits a hash before/at round start, then reveals the seed at settlement. The contract verifies the commitment.\n    85→\n    86→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    87→- [x] `store_commitment(round_pda, hash)` stores `SHA256(server_seed)` in the round PDA <!-- satisfied: commit_reveal.rs:11 store_commitment(commitment: &mut [u8; 32], hash: [u8; 32]) -->\n    88→- [x] `verify_reveal(round_pda, server_seed)` checks `SHA256(server_seed) == stored_hash` <!-- satisfied: commit_reveal.rs:16 verify_reveal(commitment, server_seed) -->\n    89→- [x] Verification failure returns a typed error (commitment mismatch) <!-- satisfied: commit_reveal.rs:5-8 CommitRevealError::CommitmentMismatch -->\n    90→- [ ] On verification failure, round transitions to REFUNDED (not SETTLED) <!-- deferred: requires commit-reveal game consumer (002-crash is Draft) -->\n    91→- [x] No third-party dependency — uses `solana_program::hash::hashv` or equivalent <!-- satisfied: commit_reveal.rs:2 uses solana_sha256_hasher::hashv (Solana SDK v2 subcrate) -->\n    92→- [x] Module is independently testable (unit tests with known hash pairs) <!-- satisfied: commit_reveal.rs:26-56 three tests: known pair, tampered seed, empty seed -->\n    93→\n    94→### FR-3: Fee Distribution\n    95→\n    96→Formalize existing fee math as the single path for all fee calculations. No game ever implements its own fee logic.\n    97→\n    98→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    99→- [x] `calculate_fee(pool_lamports) -> (fee, net_payout)` returns fee and payout amounts <!-- satisfied: fees.rs:25 calculate_net_payout(pool: u64) -> (u64, u64) -->\n   100→- [x] Fee = 300 bps (3%) of pool, hardcoded constant <!-- satisfied: fees.rs:8 TOTAL_FEE_BPS: u16 = 300 -->\n   101→- [x] `transfer_fee(round_pda, treasury_pda, fee_amount)` sends fee to treasury <!-- satisfied: escrow::transfer_lamports_from_pda used in claim_payout.rs:126 -->\n   102→- [x] Integer math only (basis points, lamports) — no floats <!-- satisfied: fees.rs:19 u128 intermediate, all integer operations -->\n   103→- [x] Rounding favors the player (fee rounds down) <!-- satisfied: fees.rs:19 integer division truncates; test :68-70 confirms 1 lamport → fee=0 -->\n   104→- [x] `MAX_FEE_BPS = 1000` compile-time safety cap preserved <!-- satisfied: fees.rs:2 MAX_FEE_BPS=1000, compile-time assertion at :14 -->\n   105→- [x] Fee split (200 bps revenue, 70 bps rakeback, 30 bps chest) tracked but single treasury transfer for V1 <!-- satisfied: fees.rs:9-11 constants match; split_fee() at :31-36; claim_payout.rs:126 single treasury transfer -->\n   106→\n   107→### FR-4: VRF Provider Integration (Orao)\n   108→\n   109→Integrate **Orao** as the single VRF provider for all games requiring randomness. Uses `orao-solana-vrf` (standard crate, not callback variant). No separate consume/resolve instruction — VRF result is read at claim time.\n   110→\n   111→**Integration Contract (Authoritative Shape):**\n   112→\n   113→- **Request path**: VRF is requested as part of an existing game instruction (e.g., `join_match` for coinflip). No separate `request_vrf` instruction.\n   114→- **Request side effects**:\n   115→  - CPIs into Orao to request randomness with a unique seed (derived from match PDA or round ID).\n   116→  - Stores `vrf_request_key` on the round account for later lookup.\n   117→  - Sets `resolve_deadline` for timeout safety.\n   118→  - Moves phase to `Locked`.\n   119→- **Read-at-claim path**: No separate consume/callback instruction. The `claim_payout` instruction reads the fulfilled Orao `Randomness` PDA (passed as an account input), verifies it's fulfilled, derives the outcome, and settles — all in one tx.\n   120→- **Frontend reads** (no tx): Frontend polls the Orao randomness PDA to detect fulfillment and show the result. This is a free read, not a transaction. Frontend maintains a **claimable games list** per user so players can claim or cancel.\n   121→- **Failure/timeout**:\n   122→  - If Orao has not fulfilled by `resolve_deadline`, any signer can trigger timeout refund (FR-5 invariants).\n   123→  - Claim with unfulfilled randomness is rejected.\n   124→\n   125→**Why not callback**: The 3-tx model (create → join+request → claim+read) is simpler. VRF latency (~1-2s) is absorbed while the frontend detects fulfillment. No callback infrastructure, no extra instruction, no cranker.\n   126→\n   127→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   128→- [x] Orao selection is documented in `docs/DECISIONS.md` <!-- satisfied: DECISIONS.md \"VRF Provider = Orao (MagicBlock dropped)\" dated 2026-02-25, Status: Locked -->\n   129→- [x] Shared helper module exists for Orao integration (`vrf_orao.rs`) — request helper, read helper, fulfillment check <!-- satisfied: vrf_orao.rs — request_orao_randomness(:31), read_orao_randomness(:57), is_fulfilled(:21) -->\n   130→- [x] VRF request is embedded in a game instruction (e.g., `join_match`), not a separate instruction <!-- satisfied: join_match.rs:78-87 Orao CPI embedded in join_match -->\n   131→- [x] `claim_payout` reads Orao randomness account at claim time, derives outcome, and settles <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:104 reads, :107-112 derives, :115-126 settles -->\n   132→- [x] Claim emits Anchor event with randomness bytes + derived outcome (audit trail persists in tx logs after match PDA closed) <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:156-163 MatchSettled with randomness + winner -->\n   133→- [x] Claim with unfulfilled Orao randomness is rejected with clear error <!-- satisfied: vrf_orao.rs:71/103 VrfError::RandomnessNotFulfilled; test \"rejects claim with unfulfilled randomness\" -->\n   134→- [x] Outcome derivation from VRF is deterministic and uses only on-chain/public inputs <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:107 from_randomness(randomness[0]) in constants.rs:15 — byte % 2 -->\n   135→- [x] Timeout path remains permissionless when VRF is not fulfilled (refund, not stuck funds) <!-- satisfied: timeout_cancel.rs:11-14 any signer, :58-70 checks deadline+VRF unfulfilled -->\n   136→- [x] `mock-vrf` feature flag: in test builds, skip Orao CPI on request and allow test authority to write mock randomness for claim <!-- satisfied: shared/Cargo.toml mock-vrf feature; vrf_orao.rs:80-91 no-op, :96-105 raw bytes -->\n   137→- [x] Reference implementation: Coinflip (001) as first consumer <!-- satisfied: coinflip program fully rewritten with shared crate + Orao VRF, 28 bankrun tests pass -->\n   138→- [x] Drop all MagicBlock VRF references from codebase and docs <!-- satisfied: grep returns zero matches in solana/ and CLAUDE.md; iteration 16 confirmed -->\n   139→\n   140→### FR-5: On-Chain Lifecycle State Machine\n   141→\n   142→Every round in every game follows the same phase progression with hard invariants. Not every game uses every phase — VRF-only games skip RESOLVING (result is read at claim time).\n   143→\n   144→```\n   145→WAITING -> ACTIVE -> LOCKED -> RESOLVING -> SETTLED\n   146→                         \\                \\-> REFUNDED (on timeout or cancel)\n   147→                          \\-> SETTLED (VRF games: claim reads result at claim time, skips RESOLVING)\n   148→```\n   149→\n   150→**Phase usage by game type:**\n   151→- **VRF-only games** (coinflip, Lord of RNGs, slots): WAITING → LOCKED → SETTLED/REFUNDED. VRF requested at lock, result read at claim. No RESOLVING needed.\n   152→- **Commit-reveal games** (crash, chart the course, game of trades): WAITING → ACTIVE → LOCKED → RESOLVING → SETTLED/REFUNDED. Server submits reveal during RESOLVING.\n   153→- **Mixed VRF + commit-reveal** (tug of earn): Uses RESOLVING for server reveal phase.\n   154→\n   155→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   156→- [x] `RoundPhase` enum: `Waiting`, `Active`, `Locked`, `Resolving`, `Settled`, `Refunded` <!-- satisfied: lifecycle.rs:5-12 all 6 variants with correct derives -->\n   157→- [x] `transition(current, target) -> Result<()>` validates allowed transitions, rejects invalid ones (including LOCKED→SETTLED for VRF games) <!-- satisfied: lifecycle.rs:39-58 nine allowed transitions; test :88-89 confirms LOCKED→SETTLED invalid -->\n   158→- [x] **Timeout invariant**: Every round entering `Locked` or `Resolving` gets a `resolve_deadline` timestamp. After expiry, anyone can trigger refund — BUT only if the resolution source (VRF or commit-reveal) has NOT been fulfilled. If VRF is fulfilled, claim must be used instead of timeout_cancel. <!-- satisfied: join_match.rs sets resolve_deadline; timeout_cancel.rs:58-70 checks deadline+VRF unfulfilled; test \"rejects timeout when VRF IS fulfilled\" -->\n   159→- [x] **Pause invariant**: Global pause (platform-level) and per-game pause (game config). Paused games reject new rounds but existing rounds can still settle or refund. <!-- satisfied: pause.rs:13 check_not_paused; create_match.rs:39 calls it; claim_payout/timeout_cancel do NOT check (settle/refund still work) -->\n   160→- [x] **Refund invariant**: Any round that doesn't reach `Settled` before its deadline AND whose resolution source is not fulfilled is refundable. No player funds get stuck. Refund is not available if a valid result exists (prevents racing claim vs refund). <!-- satisfied: timeout_cancel.rs:67-70 checks VRF NOT fulfilled; rejects if fulfilled (must claim) -->\n   161→- [ ] Phase transitions emit Anchor events for frontend consumption <!-- gap: only MatchSettled emitted (claim_payout.rs:156); create/join/cancel/timeout do not emit events -->\n   162→- [ ] Timestamp tracking: `created_at`, `locked_at`, `resolve_deadline`, `settled_at` fields <!-- gap (partial): CoinflipMatch has created_at/locked_at/resolve_deadline but NOT settled_at; shared RoundTimestamps defines all 4 but coinflip uses inline fields -->\n   163→\n   164→### FR-6: Platform CPI Helpers\n   165→\n   166→Reusable CPI calls from game programs to the platform program for updating player profiles after settlement.\n   167→\n   168→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   169→- [x] `update_player_profile(program, profile_pda, game, wins, wager, won)` CPIs into platform program <!-- satisfied: cpi.rs:41 update_player_profile_cpi with platform_program, profile, authority, signer_seeds, game/wins/wager/won deltas -->\n   170→- [x] CPI is conditional — skipped if player profile PDA does not exist (no hard failure) <!-- satisfied: cpi.rs:52-54 if profile.data_is_empty() return Ok(()) -->\n   171→- [x] Both players' profiles updated on settlement (winner and loser stats) <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:133-153 CPI for both creator and opponent; tests \"updates player profiles via CPI\" -->\n   172→- [ ] CPI helper is generic enough for all game types (accepts game discriminator) <!-- gap: no game discriminator param; platform update_player_profile lacks game type field; stats aggregated without per-game attribution -->\n   173→\n   174→---"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"71f3d66f-916b-4438-95fb-e3b573af6aa8","uuid":"4015ceed-62b8-46a9-a01e-4005c5eb6a29","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/rng-utopia/docs/specs/004-shared-infrastructure/spec.md","content":"### FR-1: Shared Crate — Escrow Helpers (Claim-Based Payout)\n\nReusable functions for depositing SOL to a round PDA and letting participants claim their funds. Uses a **claim-based payout pattern**: for VRF games, the `claim_payout` instruction reads the VRF result at claim time (no separate settle tx), derives the winner, and transfers funds — all in one tx. For commit-reveal games, the server's reveal instruction writes the outcome, then players claim. Either way, the claim instruction is what moves funds.\n\n**Three-transaction flow for VRF games (e.g., coinflip):**\n1. `create_match` — creator deposits SOL, phase = WAITING\n2. `join_match` — opponent deposits SOL, requests Orao VRF, phase = LOCKED, `resolve_deadline` set\n3. `claim_payout` — either player calls. Reads fulfilled Orao randomness account, derives winner, transfers payout + fee, emits audit event, closes match.\n\nFrontend reads the Orao randomness PDA (free, no tx) to show the result. The claim tx is what settles on-chain.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [x] `deposit_to_escrow(from, round_pda, amount)` transfers SOL from player to round PDA via system program CPI <!-- satisfied: escrow.rs:53 transfer_lamports_to_pda; used in create_match.rs:46, join_match.rs:70 -->\n- [x] `claim_payout` reads VRF result at claim time (for VRF games) or reads stored outcome (for commit-reveal games), derives winner, transfers payout <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:104 reads Orao, :107-112 derives winner, :115-126 transfers -->\n- [x] Either participant can trigger claim — payout always goes to the derived winner regardless of caller <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:79-83 allows creator/opponent, :108-112 derives winner; test \"either player can trigger claim\" -->\n- [x] Claim is idempotent — double-claim returns error, does not double-pay <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:76 checks !claimed, PDA closed after claim (:20); test \"rejects double claim\" -->\n- [x] Claim emits an Anchor event with VRF randomness bytes, derived winner, and payout amounts (audit trail — match PDA is closed after claim) <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:156-163 emits MatchSettled; state.rs:55-63 event struct -->\n- [x] `refund(round_pda, caller)` — each depositor calls individually to pull their refund after timeout <!-- satisfied: timeout_cancel.rs:74-77 refunds both via transfer_lamports_from_pda (atomic, design variance) -->\n- [x] `close_round(round_pda, rent_recipient)` closes the PDA and returns rent <!-- satisfied: Anchor close=creator constraint on claim_payout.rs:20, cancel_match.rs:17, timeout_cancel.rs:29 -->\n- [x] No escrow function touches fee math (fees handled separately in FR-3) <!-- satisfied: escrow.rs has only lamport transfer functions; fees in fees.rs, called separately in claim_payout.rs:116 -->\n- [ ] **Claimable games query**: match PDAs in LOCKED phase (VRF fulfilled) or SETTLED phase (commit-reveal settled) with `claimed == false` are discoverable via `getProgramAccounts` filter by player pubkey + phase. Frontend must maintain a \"claimable / unresolved games\" list per user. <!-- gap: frontend chain.ts only has fetchAllOpenMatches (Waiting phase); no claimable-per-user query exists -->\n\n### FR-2: Commit-Reveal Verifier\n\nSelf-built module (~50 lines Rust) for server result verification. The server commits a hash before/at round start, then reveals the seed at settlement. The contract verifies the commitment.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [x] `store_commitment(round_pda, hash)` stores `SHA256(server_seed)` in the round PDA <!-- satisfied: commit_reveal.rs:11 store_commitment(commitment: &mut [u8; 32], hash: [u8; 32]) -->\n- [x] `verify_reveal(round_pda, server_seed)` checks `SHA256(server_seed) == stored_hash` <!-- satisfied: commit_reveal.rs:16 verify_reveal(commitment, server_seed) -->\n- [x] Verification failure returns a typed error (commitment mismatch) <!-- satisfied: commit_reveal.rs:5-8 CommitRevealError::CommitmentMismatch -->\n- [ ] On verification failure, round transitions to REFUNDED (not SETTLED) <!-- deferred: requires commit-reveal game consumer (002-crash is Draft) -->\n- [x] No third-party dependency — uses `solana_program::hash::hashv` or equivalent <!-- satisfied: commit_reveal.rs:2 uses solana_sha256_hasher::hashv (Solana SDK v2 subcrate) -->\n- [x] Module is independently testable (unit tests with known hash pairs) <!-- satisfied: commit_reveal.rs:26-56 three tests: known pair, tampered seed, empty seed -->\n\n### FR-3: Fee Distribution\n\nFormalize existing fee math as the single path for all fee calculations. No game ever implements its own fee logic.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [x] `calculate_fee(pool_lamports) -> (fee, net_payout)` returns fee and payout amounts <!-- satisfied: fees.rs:25 calculate_net_payout(pool: u64) -> (u64, u64) -->\n- [x] Fee = 300 bps (3%) of pool, hardcoded constant <!-- satisfied: fees.rs:8 TOTAL_FEE_BPS: u16 = 300 -->\n- [x] `transfer_fee(round_pda, treasury_pda, fee_amount)` sends fee to treasury <!-- satisfied: escrow::transfer_lamports_from_pda used in claim_payout.rs:126 -->\n- [x] Integer math only (basis points, lamports) — no floats <!-- satisfied: fees.rs:19 u128 intermediate, all integer operations -->\n- [x] Rounding favors the player (fee rounds down) <!-- satisfied: fees.rs:19 integer division truncates; test :68-70 confirms 1 lamport → fee=0 -->\n- [x] `MAX_FEE_BPS = 1000` compile-time safety cap preserved <!-- satisfied: fees.rs:2 MAX_FEE_BPS=1000, compile-time assertion at :14 -->\n- [x] Fee split (200 bps revenue, 70 bps rakeback, 30 bps chest) tracked but single treasury transfer for V1 <!-- satisfied: fees.rs:9-11 constants match; split_fee() at :31-36; claim_payout.rs:126 single treasury transfer -->\n\n### FR-4: VRF Provider Integration (Orao)\n\nIntegrate **Orao** as the single VRF provider for all games requiring randomness. Uses `orao-solana-vrf` (standard crate, not callback variant). No separate consume/resolve instruction — VRF result is read at claim time.\n\n**Integration Contract (Authoritative Shape):**\n\n- **Request path**: VRF is requested as part of an existing game instruction (e.g., `join_match` for coinflip). No separate `request_vrf` instruction.\n- **Request side effects**:\n  - CPIs into Orao to request randomness with a unique seed (derived from match PDA or round ID).\n  - Stores `vrf_request_key` on the round account for later lookup.\n  - Sets `resolve_deadline` for timeout safety.\n  - Moves phase to `Locked`.\n- **Read-at-claim path**: No separate consume/callback instruction. The `claim_payout` instruction reads the fulfilled Orao `Randomness` PDA (passed as an account input), verifies it's fulfilled, derives the outcome, and settles — all in one tx.\n- **Frontend reads** (no tx): Frontend polls the Orao randomness PDA to detect fulfillment and show the result. This is a free read, not a transaction. Frontend maintains a **claimable games list** per user so players can claim or cancel.\n- **Failure/timeout**:\n  - If Orao has not fulfilled by `resolve_deadline`, any signer can trigger timeout refund (FR-5 invariants).\n  - Claim with unfulfilled randomness is rejected.\n\n**Why not callback**: The 3-tx model (create → join+request → claim+read) is simpler. VRF latency (~1-2s) is absorbed while the frontend detects fulfillment. No callback infrastructure, no extra instruction, no cranker.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [x] Orao selection is documented in `docs/DECISIONS.md` <!-- satisfied: DECISIONS.md \"VRF Provider = Orao (MagicBlock dropped)\" dated 2026-02-25, Status: Locked -->\n- [x] Shared helper module exists for Orao integration (`vrf_orao.rs`) — request helper, read helper, fulfillment check <!-- satisfied: vrf_orao.rs — request_orao_randomness(:31), read_orao_randomness(:57), is_fulfilled(:21) -->\n- [x] VRF request is embedded in a game instruction (e.g., `join_match`), not a separate instruction <!-- satisfied: join_match.rs:78-87 Orao CPI embedded in join_match -->\n- [x] `claim_payout` reads Orao randomness account at claim time, derives outcome, and settles <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:104 reads, :107-112 derives, :115-126 settles -->\n- [x] Claim emits Anchor event with randomness bytes + derived outcome (audit trail persists in tx logs after match PDA closed) <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:156-163 MatchSettled with randomness + winner -->\n- [x] Claim with unfulfilled Orao randomness is rejected with clear error <!-- satisfied: vrf_orao.rs:71/103 VrfError::RandomnessNotFulfilled; test \"rejects claim with unfulfilled randomness\" -->\n- [x] Outcome derivation from VRF is deterministic and uses only on-chain/public inputs <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:107 from_randomness(randomness[0]) in constants.rs:15 — byte % 2 -->\n- [x] Timeout path remains permissionless when VRF is not fulfilled (refund, not stuck funds) <!-- satisfied: timeout_cancel.rs:11-14 any signer, :58-70 checks deadline+VRF unfulfilled -->\n- [x] `mock-vrf` feature flag: in test builds, skip Orao CPI on request and allow test authority to write mock randomness for claim <!-- satisfied: shared/Cargo.toml mock-vrf feature; vrf_orao.rs:80-91 no-op, :96-105 raw bytes -->\n- [x] Reference implementation: Coinflip (001) as first consumer <!-- satisfied: coinflip program fully rewritten with shared crate + Orao VRF, 28 bankrun tests pass -->\n- [x] Drop all MagicBlock VRF references from codebase and docs <!-- satisfied: grep returns zero matches in solana/ and CLAUDE.md; iteration 16 confirmed -->\n\n### FR-5: On-Chain Lifecycle State Machine\n\nEvery round in every game follows the same phase progression with hard invariants. Not every game uses every phase — VRF-only games skip RESOLVING (result is read at claim time).\n\n```\nWAITING -> ACTIVE -> LOCKED -> RESOLVING -> SETTLED\n                         \\                \\-> REFUNDED (on timeout or cancel)\n                          \\-> SETTLED (VRF games: claim reads result at claim time, skips RESOLVING)\n```\n\n**Phase usage by game type:**\n- **VRF-only games** (coinflip, Lord of RNGs, slots): WAITING → LOCKED → SETTLED/REFUNDED. VRF requested at lock, result read at claim. No RESOLVING needed.\n- **Commit-reveal games** (crash, chart the course, game of trades): WAITING → ACTIVE → LOCKED → RESOLVING → SETTLED/REFUNDED. Server submits reveal during RESOLVING.\n- **Mixed VRF + commit-reveal** (tug of earn): Uses RESOLVING for server reveal phase.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [x] `RoundPhase` enum: `Waiting`, `Active`, `Locked`, `Resolving`, `Settled`, `Refunded` <!-- satisfied: lifecycle.rs:5-12 all 6 variants with correct derives -->\n- [x] `transition(current, target) -> Result<()>` validates allowed transitions, rejects invalid ones (including LOCKED→SETTLED for VRF games) <!-- satisfied: lifecycle.rs:39-58 nine allowed transitions; test :88-89 confirms LOCKED→SETTLED invalid -->\n- [x] **Timeout invariant**: Every round entering `Locked` or `Resolving` gets a `resolve_deadline` timestamp. After expiry, anyone can trigger refund — BUT only if the resolution source (VRF or commit-reveal) has NOT been fulfilled. If VRF is fulfilled, claim must be used instead of timeout_cancel. <!-- satisfied: join_match.rs sets resolve_deadline; timeout_cancel.rs:58-70 checks deadline+VRF unfulfilled; test \"rejects timeout when VRF IS fulfilled\" -->\n- [x] **Pause invariant**: Global pause (platform-level) and per-game pause (game config). Paused games reject new rounds but existing rounds can still settle or refund. <!-- satisfied: pause.rs:13 check_not_paused; create_match.rs:39 calls it; claim_payout/timeout_cancel do NOT check (settle/refund still work) -->\n- [x] **Refund invariant**: Any round that doesn't reach `Settled` before its deadline AND whose resolution source is not fulfilled is refundable. No player funds get stuck. Refund is not available if a valid result exists (prevents racing claim vs refund). <!-- satisfied: timeout_cancel.rs:67-70 checks VRF NOT fulfilled; rejects if fulfilled (must claim) -->\n- [ ] Phase transitions emit Anchor events for frontend consumption <!-- gap: only MatchSettled emitted (claim_payout.rs:156); create/join/cancel/timeout do not emit events -->\n- [ ] Timestamp tracking: `created_at`, `locked_at`, `resolve_deadline`, `settled_at` fields <!-- gap (partial): CoinflipMatch has created_at/locked_at/resolve_deadline but NOT settled_at; shared RoundTimestamps defines all 4 but coinflip uses inline fields -->\n\n### FR-6: Platform CPI Helpers\n\nReusable CPI calls from game programs to the platform program for updating player profiles after settlement.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [x] `update_player_profile(program, profile_pda, game, wins, wager, won)` CPIs into platform program <!-- satisfied: cpi.rs:41 update_player_profile_cpi with platform_program, profile, authority, signer_seeds, game/wins/wager/won deltas -->\n- [x] CPI is conditional — skipped if player profile PDA does not exist (no hard failure) <!-- satisfied: cpi.rs:52-54 if profile.data_is_empty() return Ok(()) -->\n- [x] Both players' profiles updated on settlement (winner and loser stats) <!-- satisfied: claim_payout.rs:133-153 CPI for both creator and opponent; tests \"updates player profiles via CPI\" -->\n- [ ] CPI helper is generic enough for all game types (accepts game discriminator) <!-- gap: no game discriminator param; platform update_player_profile lacks game type field; stats aggregated without per-game attribution -->\n\n---","numLines":115,"startLine":60,"totalLines":297}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01QZD2YCXpcWUerAVrm968wU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The spec already has the HTML comment annotations from the previous gap analysis. Let me check if the line numbers have changed for any of the references. I've now verified the actual code:\n\n1. `escrow.rs:53` → Actually `transfer_lamports_to_pda` is at line 53, confirmed.\n2. `claim_payout.rs:104` → `read_orao_randomness` at line 104, confirmed.\n3. `claim_payout.rs:79-83` → Caller validation at lines 79-83, confirmed.\n4. `claim_payout.rs:76` → `!claimed` check at line 76, confirmed.\n\n\n5. `claim_payout.rs:156-163` → Event emission for match settlement at lines 156-163, confirmed.\n6. `timeout_cancel.rs:75-77` → The refund logic is actually at lines 75-77, not 74 as originally noted.\n7. `claim_payout.rs:20` → Account closure assignment at line 20, confirmed.\n8. `timeout_cancel.rs:29` → Account closure assignment at line 29, confirmed.\n9. `fees.rs:8` → Total fee basis points constant at line 8, confirmed.\n10. `fees.rs:2` → Maximum fee basis points constant at line 2, confirmed.\n11. `fees.rs:19` → Integer arithmetic for fee calculations at line 19, confirmed.\n12. `lifecycle.rs:5-12` → Round phase enumeration at lines 5-12, confirmed.\n13. `lifecycle.rs:39-58` → State transition logic at lines 39-58, confirmed.\n14. `vrf_orao.rs:21` → Fulfillment check at line 21, confirmed.\n15. `vrf_orao.rs:31` → Randomness request function at line 31, confirmed.\n16. Continuing through the remaining file references... Continuing through the remaining function locations — pause.rs has the check_not_paused function, state.rs contains the MatchSettled event and paused field, and cpi.rs has the update_player_profile_cpi function with its data_is_empty validation. For timeout_cancel.rs, I'm verifying the signer caller logic and the deadline check spans a slightly different range than initially noted.\n\nLooking at the spec annotations themselves, most line references are accurate within a line or two. I'm catching a few that need adjustment — the refund calls in timeout_cancel.rs are actually at lines 75-77 rather than 74-77, and the test count annotation appears off since there are 31 total tests, not 28.\n\nBut I'm realizing the task constraints are clear: I should only be annotating the FR acceptance criteria checkboxes, not modifying the implementation checklist or making broad spec updates. The annotations that exist are close enough for audit purposes, so I should focus on what was actually requested. I'm going through the line number references to make sure they're still accurate. Most of them check out within a line or two, which is fine for audit purposes. The main thing I need to fix is updating the test count in FR-4 AC-10 from 28 to 26 bankrun tests, since that's the most material change. The rest of the annotations are solid enough to leave as-is.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4424,"cache_read_input_tokens":108110,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4424},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"71f3d66f-916b-4438-95fb-e3b573af6aa8","uuid":"7bd7355d-017c-4335-8e8a-33325100a5ed"}
